# Getting Started with GitHub

> "GitHub feels like a giant workshop where programmers store and collaborate on code. Almost everyone is confused the first time they use it."

This guide will take you from zero to your first open-source contribution in about 30 minutes.

---

## 1. Learn the Essentials (5 mins)

Understand the core concepts before exploring the interface:

- **Git** — A version control system that tracks changes to your code over time
- **GitHub** — A platform built on top of Git that lets you collaborate with others
- **Repository (repo)** — A project folder that contains all your code and its history
- **Commit** — A saved snapshot of your code at a specific point in time
- **Branch** — A separate line of development, useful for working on features without affecting the main code
- **Pull Request (PR)** — A proposal to merge changes from one branch into another
- **Issue** — A way to report bugs, request features, or discuss improvements
- **Fork** — A copy of someone else's repository that you own and can modify

---

## 2. Explore a Real Repository (10 mins)

Visit any public repository and find these key areas:

- 📁 **Files** — The actual code and project structure
- 📖 **README** — A guide explaining what the project does and how to use it
- 📋 **Issues** — Bug reports and feature requests from the community
- 🔀 **Pull Requests** — Proposed changes waiting for review
- 💬 **Discussions** — Community conversations about the project
- ⭐ **Star** — How you bookmark projects you like
- 🍴 **Fork** — How you create your own copy to experiment with

---

## 3. Practice with Your Own Repository (5 mins)

Create a test project to get comfortable with the basics:

- [ ] Create a new repository
- [ ] Upload or create a file
- [ ] Edit a file directly on GitHub
- [ ] Commit your changes with a message
- [ ] View your commit history and explore what changed

---

## 4. Make Your First Open-Source Contribution (10 mins)

Once comfortable, try contributing to an existing project:

- Fork a repository (create your own copy)
- Create a new branch (separate workspace for your changes)
- Make changes (fix a bug or add a feature)
- Open a Pull Request (propose your changes to the original project)

---

## Best Resources for Beginners

- **[GitHub Skills](https://skills.github.com)** — Interactive hands-on lessons where you practice directly on GitHub. Perfect if you learn by doing.

- **[GitHub Docs](https://docs.github.com)** — Official documentation with beginner-friendly guides. Great for detailed explanations and reference.

- **[First Contributions](https://firstcontributions.github.io)** — Step-by-step tutorial designed specifically for your first open-source contribution.

- **[Oh My Git!](https://ohmygit.org)** — A free game that teaches Git concepts in a fun, interactive way.

---

## The Quick Mental Model

Think of GitHub like this: **Google Drive + version history + collaboration for code.**

- Every **repository** is a project
- Every **commit** is a saved version (like "Version 1.0", "Version 1.1", etc.)
- **Pull Requests** are how people propose changes and get them reviewed
- **Branches** are like working on a copy without messing up the original

---

## What's Next?

Once you've completed these steps:

- Start contributing to projects you care about
- Learn about code review and giving feedback on PRs
- Explore GitHub Actions for automating tasks
- Set up your GitHub profile to showcase your work
